			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Hey guys, I don't normally post on these boards, especially the debates and rants sections cause I hate the flaming.  This post caught my eye though and I have to speak my own mind about this subject. 
<br />
   I am currently deployed to a small country called Qatar of the tip of Saudi Arabia.  I have been over here for just under 3 months now and I have to say it has opened my eyes to many things.  Never once did I think that this war was all about the oil, and regardless of the politics behind it I think my military brothers and sisters have accomplished great things for the people of the Middle East.  
<br />
   Aludeid AB, Qatar is a main hub of transportation for supplies, troops, and other things needed to support the war that most people only see from their living room.  People sit in their comfortable recliners and drink pure water on tap with all the food they want watching TV, complaining that we are over here wasting their money.  Our efforts here are not pointless and to all who think they are, you are sadly mistaken.  Upon my arrival here at Qatar, just before the capture of Saddam, we were briefed that the Terrorist threat in this region is VERY high.  Sure enough, not two months later, 
<br />
<a href="http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/02/13/qatar.chechen/index.html" target="_blank">http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/meast/02/13/qatar.chechen/index.html</a>
<br />
our base was dramatically placed in Charlie and all off-base travel was suspended.  If you click the link you'll see why, but basically there was an attack outside Doha.  Just yesterday I had the opportunity to go downtown and see the city and outskirts of Doha for myself.  I met an Iraqi family eating lunch that had just moved to Qatar and found work, purchasing their first family car and house.  This family was actually set better financially than the average I gather.  I get to eat lunch daily with the army and marine forces that are just getting a chance to come home and see their family for the first time since the Iraqi invasion.  Many of these forces as well as a countless number of brits, tell me what it's like in Baghdad.  I am just a simple airman in the USAF, quite removed from anything you could label as danger.   These guys are heroes.  I would say that not one of these men went against their will to go fight in Iraq.  Sure in the military if you don't like something, too bad; but every one of these troops I would venture to say believe that what this country is doing over here is the morally right thing.  I see pictures of Iraqi children going to school unafraid to walk through the streets, I see mothers allowed to stand up and become something now.  I see all of the restrictions placed upon this country slowly being lifted, as this truly is operation Iraqi freedom.  Sit in you’re @#%$ recliner and tarnish the reputations of those who gave their lives for a greater cause, it’s your right.  Question all you want the motive of our president and the forces of the United States.  Then think of all the simple freedoms that you daily take for granted.  Then, imagine a world where none of these freedoms exist, and you have no rights.  Next, thank God (if you even believe) that he allows you to be a part of a nation where you don't have to live life like that.  Nobody's life is perfect, and from first hand experience its one thing to see it on CNN, its totally different once you see it for yourself.  God bless you all and take to heart the sacrifices that these people make to allow us all the freedoms we have.
<br />

<br />
Zachary Wagle<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
