			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				And in Elbrichs posts again we see clearly illustrated the fault in his logical chain.  Not only in his own words but in teh words of his supporting evidence as well.
<br />

<br />
You posted an Iraqis views of of the occupation as evidence that Iraqis are unhappy.  Yet when you read it, you find that the person really has to reach for displeasure and make some fundamental emotional leaps of reason to base their position.
<br />

<br />
Throughout their piont by point dissection of the list of good things, this person is unable to fault the US though they try to allude to resposnibility they shy away in their own writing mid paragraph and say things like, "but this is not the fault of the US."
<br />

<br />
The strongest of their arguements against the US is this:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Yes things are getting better, but very slowly. In fact it is so slow that we are not expecting things to get back to normal in months to come. We modified our hopes from few months, to few years and we are very sad to have reached this conclusion.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
To me this belies the person having expectations that are way outside the bounds of reality or rational thought.  The government was deposed by military force.  It was a revolution and it was swift.  Things WILL NOT get better in Iraq "fast" when it comes to matters of infrastructure.  Even slower will be the adoption of a non-tyrranical form of government.  The mindset in Iraq has long been programmed to accept that sort of rule.  There will be some hard lessons coming in the future for Iraqis. That is the PRICE OF FREEDOM... It is called RESPONSIBILITY and it is a major pain in the a.ss.
<br />

<br />
This Iraqi you post as evidence is still in a denial phase.  They want Iraq to prosper, and they want  it to be sovereign.  The want it to happen overnight without having to work towards it happening. They want to have their cake and to eat it too.
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
You sir, are also in a denail phase.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Look up the Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002. It is too big to post. It has some good information on the reasons for going to war. Once you know the reasons don't stop there. Question their validity. Question their success. Question the posiblity of their success.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I do not question their validity. None of them.  They are all based on a nations right to defend itself from a threat.  The inclusion of principles that protect the interests of Iraqi people are gifts that the Iraqi People would not have thought twice about had the roles been reversed.  I have centuries of evidence to back that statement up.
<br />

<br />
To sit there and collectively whine about unreal forcasts and expectations is ludacrice.  To the person you linked and also to you, sir, if you are so concerned that the US is not securing domestic traquility in Iraq, what are YOU doing about it?
<br />

<br />
For the person you linked I also say, Iraq is YOUR country, you should be out there engineering peace.  If you want the liberty you must take the responsibility.  DO SO and stop whining.
<br />

<br />
To you Elbrich, may I suggest that you look into supporting a group like Doctors Without Borders.  If you want to criticize, you should at least have the cajones to back up your concerns with real and positive action.  
<br />

<br />
Then, again, I dont think that the welfare of the Iraqi people is at all your concern.
<br />

<br />
It is wholely a rhetorical game <img src="images/smiles/wink.gif" alt="wink" border="0" /><br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
