<br />

<br />
If you have a chance take a read of this from the Strategic Studies Institute of the U.S. Army War College. It's not exactly what you are asking but is strongly related.  It was posted previously. You may also want to check out a book called <span style="text-decoration: underline">The Sorrows of Empire</span>.  I've only taken a quick flip through it but it presents some interesting avenues of though. <a href="http://duncan.statusbar.com/bounding.pdf" target="_blank">http://duncan.statusbar.com/bounding.pdf</a> 
<br />

<br />
I can come up with a list of good things too if you like.  I don't deny that many good things have happened because of the war.  However, I don't think they are worth the continuing cost.
<br />

<br />
I should also add... While I don't think the USA and Britain should have gone to war, I think that leaving now would make a bad situation worse.  Huge respect for the servicemen over there coping admirably with a difficult situation.
<br />

<br />
